% explaining the sigma symmetry 
\begin{frame}{$\sigma$}
 %”The last type of symmetry is sigma, we will come back to that. Instead lets look at what happens when we apply multiple symmetries to the same polygon”
There is a third type of symmetry called $\sigma$ (sigma). We will come back to this later. 
\end{frame}

% more definitions 
\begin{frame}{Definitions}
    Cayley Table: Arranges all the possible products of a group's elements.
   \\\vspace{5pt}
    Group: A set of elements combined with an operation
    \\\vspace{5pt}
    Dihedral Group: A group of symmetries of a regular polygon which includes rotations and reflections 
    \\\vspace{5pt}
\end{frame}

% explaining what dihedral groups
\begin{frame}{Dihedral Groups}
If you just consider the symmetries formed only by $\rho$ and $\mu$, those symmetries form the exact same sets as the dihedral group. \\\vspace{15pt}
This is partly because with the rose window you are looking at the outside polygon, the inside one will follow along.\\\vspace{15pt}
    %"Lets look at those symmetries applied to the smaller $n$ examples to prove this"
\end{frame}

